</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,152,402]" pageId="12" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,226,252]" pageId="12" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[339,462,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Nysius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picipes">
<emphasis box="[339,462,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="41">N. picipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[798,916,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Nysius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vinitor">
<emphasis box="[798,916,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="41">N. vinitor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs from it in the following: legs (particularly femora) almost completely uniformly black; extensive areas on head, scutellum, and pronotum, and areas on hemelytra, fuscous; thoracic pleura and abdominal venter mostly fuscous in male, with more extensive fuscous patches in female; spermatheca rather short, apical part slightly narrower than subapical part.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
